The Power Button is the wrong place for accessing something used on a daily basis. It still has the connotation of only being used, when something's wrong. Also, the Power button being a mechanical switch that's only made for being used a couple thousand times (I mean, honestly, how often do you still long-press the power button on your phone), it will break faster. This is especially true, since, as opposed to Apple products, Android Smartphones come from a number of different manufacturers, each with different Quality Assurance.
On my current Oneplus 6T, the Power Button has been broken for the past half year, and that's only from normal use.
Basically, what Google is looking for is some quick access area that's not the overhead menu, since that's already very cluttered, as it is.

The wholesale embrace of Application-Specific Integrated Circuits (ASIC) mining for Bitcoin (BTC) could increase the cost of a 51% attack by a factor of up to 2,000.

Rod Garratt University of California Santa Barbara presented the research he co-authored with Maarten van Oordt from the Bank of Canada at the Unitize conference on July 10.

It examined the varying costs of a 51% attack on the Bitcoin network based on the type of equipment used to secure the network. The research suggests by simply switching the network 100% ASIC miners ongoing security can be enhanced greatly.

The main reason is because ASIC miners have little use, and little value, outside of Bitcoin mining and an attacker would not be able to obtain much of a return from the sale of equipment used in an attack. Consequently, in order to perform a profitable attack, they would need to double spend a much higher volume of coins, which is more costly and difficult to do.

The research estimated that for an attack occurring after the next halving to be profitable, it would require between 157,000 - 530,000 Bitcoin if 100% ASIC mining was in place.

What is a 51% attack?
A 51% attack is when a malicious participant seeks to manipulate a blockchain network by controlling 51% of the mining power (this is the minimum needed to accept new blocks). The attacker then creates an alternate chain of blocks to the ‚Äòreal‚Äô chain, and transitions the rest of the network to accept the new, manipulated chain as the correct one.

The most common use-case for this style of attack is to spend the same coins twice, commonly referred to as a double spend.

Concerns over Bitcoin‚Äôs security
Some in the Bitcoin community are adverse to ASIC miners, which caused a hard fork in 2017 that resulted in ASIC-resistant Bitcoin Gold being created. Garratt said this was why Bitcoin Gold had a number of successful 51% attacks resulting in the double-spend of $18 million in coins, while Bitcoin is yet to receive its first successful attack. However, it is vastly more expensive to attack Bitcoin, which is also a big factor.

To each their own but I prefer 3rd party launchers over any existing stock launcher. My go to is Smart Launcher with the biggest feature of it being categorized apps. It massively reduces screen clutter and removes the need for a search engine since I can just swipe to my app page, tap on media category and am only shown stuff like YouTube, Spotify, Twitch, Images, and any other related apps. These are also all automatically done, can be manually reorganized by simply holding and dragging, and even hide preinstalled apps to a hidden area you don't want to see or have already placed on your home screen as the most commonly used.
The best part about it all is that if you ever change phones or Android versions, you'll always have the exact same and familiar experience that already beats any other default launcher. This is without exaggeration, I've gotten my entire family, cousins, and friends who have Android to use a 3rd party launcher. Specifically Smart Launcher since it's my favorite out of the top ones out there.
